File: The poor South African manufacturing figures come against a backdrop of growing concerns about the health of the global economy and, in particular, South Africa’s trading partners in Europe. JOHANNESBURG - Manufacturing activity in South Africa is at its lowest levels since the global economic crisis in 2009. The latest Absa manufacturing purchasing managers' index dropped from 45.7 points in August to 41.6 points in September, a 10-year low. WATCH: Consumer saving at lowest levels in 100 years The data is an indication of policy uncertainty and dwindling business confidence in the country. Aside from sustained weak local demand, the poor South African manufacturing figures come against a backdrop of growing concerns about the health of the global economy and, in particular, South Africa’s trading partners in Europe. The dismal picture means the environment is expected to worsen further going forward.